<TITLE> President, CA condemn Mumbai attacks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 27 (bdnews24.com)--President Iajuddin Ahmed and chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed Thursday condemned the terror attacks in Mumbai and expressed solidarity with Delhi. In a message to his Indian counterpart Prativa Patil, Iajuddin Ahmed said, "Bangladesh stands firm with her friends in India at this hour of grief. The president expressed his deep shock and sorrow at the loss of lives and conveyed his deepest sympathies to the bereaved families in India. Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed, in his message to Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, "condemned the acts of terror - which were unleashed on the city of Mumbai last night - as heinous crimes." Fakhruddin expressed the hope that the release of all hostages would be speedy. The chief adviser also conveyed his sympathies to members of the bereaved families and prayed for an early recovery of the injured. India was reeling after 101 people were killed Wednesday night in a series of deadly shootings in the Indian commercial hub, the army later battling the terrorists as they took scores of foreigners hostage at the city's two top hotels. bdn
